justification:
This is a rare early drawing by Louis Kahn, Library at Philips Exeter Academy, Plan and Elevations, ca. 1967. This work is one of the few drawings for the Library project that is not in the Kahn Collection at the University of Pennsylvania which holds the Louis Kahn archive. 
&amp;nbsp;
The Library at Philips Exeter Academy (1965-72) is acknowledged to be among Louis Kahn’s most successful and admired buildings. The handsome structure stands eighty feet high and 111 feet on all four sides. Its façade is primarily brick with teak wood panels. The building’s chamfered corners allow viewers to view the brick as an exterior screen that supports only the outer most area of the four-storey building topped by a pergola open to the sky. The proposed drawing shares the medium and drawing manner with many of Kahn’s drawings. It is executed in charcoal on a thin yellow tracing paper and has an immediate, almost messy, quality due to the friable medium and the architect’s handling of the drawing. While it appears to be simply a building plan, it is much more. Contained within the drawing are studies for interior elevations and the organization of spaces in two and three dimensions.
&amp;nbsp;
What is immediately recognizable from the plan is the building’s concentric organization. Such a central-plan building was common during the Renaissance when the circle was identified with the divine and considered the most noble of architectural forms. According to a member of Kahn’s firm, the architect, who was a very spiritual thinker, thought of all of his buildings as temples. Kahn thought of the Library as a Temple for Learning and the books as spiritual offerings. He said, “You never pay the price for a book; you only pay for the printing.”
&amp;nbsp;
Kahn envisioned the Library as containing three separate functions which are apparent in the plan. The reading area, the book storage, and the place of meeting take the form of two contiguous donuts surrounding a central atrium. The reading area is concentrated in the perimeter donut where the student carrels are placed against the windows. This was where, as Kahn said, the books were “brought into the light.” This portion of the building was expressed on the outside by the brick screen and connecting brick arches supporting the outer donut. The middle donut is concrete to support the book stacks out of the direct daylight. The central forty-foot wide atrium is the place of meeting, communion and communication. Also visible on the proposed drawing is a perspective sketch for a circular arcade which became incorporated on the lowest level of the Library under the carrels and also along the perimeter of the roof. The drawing further contains three elevations that show the architect working out ideas for the wall elevations around the central atrium.
&amp;nbsp;
The drawing presents Kahn's early ideas for the building which were changed in the final structure. Early in the design process, Kahn thought to locate the service spaces (stairs, toilets) in circular or rectangular towers located at the corners of the building. Later in the process, he pulled the service spaces into the body of the structure itself which may be represented by the black squares located diagonally to the service towers. Also visible in the drawing are what became two large concrete cross beams that support the shaft above the atrium and funnel the light down into the reception area below.
&amp;nbsp;
When architectural historians write about the Exeter Library, they mention several sources for Kahn’s ideas which the architect himself mentioned. One was the Medieval cloister, especially the cloister of Durham Cathedral, of which Kahn read the following description. “The Cloister colonnade was glazed (with glass) from floor to ceiling and carrels equipped with desks set into every window niche… on the other side of the cloister against the wall of the church and away from the sunlight were placed great wooden cabinets full of books.&quot; This idea of having the books brought from the cabinets into the light for reading, led to the placement of the carrels at the outer edge of the Library, immediately behind the brick façade.
&amp;nbsp;
Another precedent was the 1785 design for a Royal Library in the Bibliothèque Nationale by the neoclassical architect Étienne-Louis Boullée. In this great barrel-vaulted space lit from above, one sees three sections of books rising in steps up the walls on all four sides. Inspired by Boullée’s example, Kahn,wanted the books to be immediately apparent to users who walked into the building. This design goal is addressed in the proposed drawing in the three separate elevations to the right of the plan. The lowest sketch of a domed structure with four circular openings below follows Kahn's ideas for the exterior of the dormitories for delegates and visitors that are adjacent to the Assembly Building at Dahka which Kahn was designing at the same time as the Library. At Exeter, he brings the bold geometries of the Indian buildings into the Library interior where the double circles become one monumental circular opening cut out of concrete on each of the atrium walls. These openings allow the book stacks to appear dramatically upon entry into the central hall. Kahn was well aware of the theatrics he had orchestrated in the atrium.&amp;nbsp; He wanted students to be humbled by the experience of entering the central space and to recognize the Library’s identity as a place where the intellect and book knowledge are paramount.
&amp;nbsp;
